</span></h3><p class="sc-jHkVzv jQDaRw pf-47774a3c8a4e-11_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fIosxK dnoTqD pf-47774a3c8a4e-13_">Think of the sympathetic nervous system as the ‘fight or flight’ manager. It prepares your body to respond to emergencies or vigorous activity. When the SNS is activated, your heart rate speeds up, your pupils dilate, and your body releases adrenaline to help you react quickly. It’s like the alarm system that gets your body ready to face danger or tackle physical challenges.</span></p></div></div></div><div class="sc-iqseJM ducrfW pf-47774a3c8a4e-14_ pf-r pf-c-cm" style="--s-xs:0px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-md:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fHeRUh cCunWv pf-47774a3c8a4e-15_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-bTfYFJ fFWOZc pf-47774a3c8a4e-16_ pf-heading-1-h3">Parasympathetic Nervous System</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-eLwHnm eiMYhK pf-47774a3c8a4e-18_ pf-heading-1-h3"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fIosxK dnoTqD pf-47774a3c8a4e-20_">Rest and Relax</span></h3><p class="sc-jHkVzv jQDaRw pf-47774a3c8a4e-21_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fIosxK dnoTqD pf-47774a3c8a4e-23_">On the other side of the coin, the parasympathetic nervous system is like the ‘rest and digest’ caretaker. It takes over once the perceived danger has passed, helping your body calm down and return to a relaxed state. It slows your heart rate, aids digestion, and allows your body to recover and repair. The PNS can be seen as the ‘chill-out’ system that promotes relaxation and rejuvenation.</span></p></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-md:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fHeRUh cCunWv pf-47774a3c8a4e-24_"><div data-pf-type="Youtube" class="sc-eXlEPa QQQel pf-47774a3c8a4e-25_"><div style="position:relative;padding-bottom:56.25%"><iframe class="pf-ifr" src="https://www.youtube.com/em